<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Dave Holladay (CYS0046)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Page </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dave Holladay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (CYS0046)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My name is Dave Holladay I have been involved in transport and cycling since the age of 12 when I began a delivery round using a bicycle, and riding widely around London &amp; Home Counties.  I have followed a career in engineering and transport, working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">variously for British Rail, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sustrans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and CTC over a period of 38 years. I now work as an independent integrated transport specialist.  My main modes of transport are on foot, cycle, and train, although I have held a driving licence since 1970, and driven a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> variety of vehicles including motorcycles, and towed trailers</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are 5 key details which I feel are not being fully addressed by current transport strategies to make cycling safer in London and other busy towns and cities, with especial reference to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disportionate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involvement of large vehicles (LGV and PCV) in fatal and serious injury crashes with pedestrians and cyclists.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">First Issue – Eye Contact prevents any other contact</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> measure concerns how we promote safer use of the roads for all witho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ut any ’victim blaming’ bias and in a universal message applicable to every road user.  I’ve had this concept developing over the past 15-20 years, and it is slowly beginning to get considered in some of the safety advice being given.  I’d get far </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more blu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> about the message and put it in front of every vehicle driver every time they get behind the wheel, every pedestrian, and every cyclist and motorcyclist.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Black'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The ONLY CONTACT you want to make with another road user  </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Black'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Black'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is    </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Arial Black'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Black'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">EYE CONTACT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have evolved a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s a species to have our optic nerve as the most direct conduit of information to the brain, and most of the information we process goes in by this route. Likewise eyes and facial expression deliver an inherently understood outward </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">communication, especially</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which shows the other party is reacting to your presence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Eye contact is already refined to a survival skill by pedestrians using Zebra </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the withering look that says “You are going to stop for me” through the windscreen to a driver.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Eye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s are only a third of the picture though and our survival over several million years has also depended on the 360</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 24/7 back-up system that lets us know about what we haven’t seen – every road user with hearing needs to use it. You will see most profession</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al drivers always </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a driver’s window slightly open so they can hear the world outside. Sounds can alert a driver to tyre noise from a vehicle in their blind spot, a shout or other warning to get them to look out for a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hazard,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and even to road surface c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onditions – tyre noise virtually disappears on sheet ice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Drivers need to be encouraged to use the horn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for the only legally permitted reason and use it gently to secure a reaction from another road user who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not responded with eye contact of a sign tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t they are aware of other road users.  I’m not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quiet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sure yet of how that message can be put across though.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; page-break-before:always; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Appended pictures are of my own early sketches for rear panel safety posters, and a reasonably good effort used by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sucklings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on their tanker fleet.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The Second Issue – Design of Vehicles Inhibiting Eye Contact</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The committee should seriously question why</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> large vehicles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> used on streets in the city have to have driving positions which have inherent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> inhibited direct vision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of other road users immediately alongside the vehicle, and have instead a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> reliance on secondary vision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> via mirrors and CCTV, further enhanced by buzzers and other devices which in turn introduce a potential to fail in correct operation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consciencious</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> driv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ers are voicing concern that through requiring them to monitor an ever increasing number of mirrors and screens they are less able to focus on the basic task of driving.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> NOT essential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to have the driver perched high above the road for vehicles drivi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng around in urban areas, indeed the ’tractor units’ that tow a ’trailer’ weighing in at 500 Tons and 24 metres high have a walk-in cab. There may even be fuel and other savings in some cases through the ability to have a lower, more compact, vehicle overa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ll.  I am aware that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and SMMT have been in discussion with around 6 truck manufacturers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and  introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of a condition to require all trucks operating on specific contracts to meet criteria for direct vision between the driver and pedestrians and cy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clists outside would be no different to those specifying low floor buses for services, and low emission engines for all large vehicles entering London.  Given the rates of failure for trucks at annual testing it may be that a 7-10 year horizon could be set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for making the standard urban truck.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The walk-in cab has advantages for drivers and crew as well, Such cabs are now widely specified for refuse collection vehicles with a few exceptions, including to my disappointment, Glasgow, where the trucks are, I ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve been advised, purchased purely on best prices. The core reason for the low cabs has little to do with cyclist safety, collection crews have a notable rate for injuries sustained slipping when climbing up into high cabs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It may be an ironic but useful d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etail that the delivery of safer truck cabs for pedestrians and cyclists will be because the cabs are actually causing injuries to the drivers climbing in and out, or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a reduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fuel consumption is delivered through the lower, cleaner profile.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The appendic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es show detail of low cab vehicles – and I commend viewing especially the end of part 2, of Robin Webb’s memorial video to his daughter – killed by a truck in London - to emphasise the value of direct vision between the driver and those outside the truck.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Third Issue – Why do 32T 4 axle construction site trucks predominate in crashes</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It cannot has escaped notice that the dominant type of truck in fatal crashes is the 4-axle 32T rigid vehicle, the maximum size that can be driven on a class C licence, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the ’currency’ for moving materials on and of construction sites in London. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> own research shows that the 44T articulated vehicles carry 50% more payload, do less damage to the roads, create less pollution, and can cost less to operate. BUT the supply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of good class E drivers is attracted to regular, clean, work driving for retail and logistics. My comment (Fifth) relates to monitoring and management to identify the drivers of lowest standard who appear to also feature </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disportionately</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in fatal crashes (D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Putz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Joao Lopes, Darren Foster </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">et</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seq</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most large tractor &amp; semi-trailer, and drawbar trailer combinations do not come in to the city if this can be avoided – it is simply unviable to have a rig costing up to £300,000 crawling around at 20Kph or le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ss racking up costly driver time etc, when it should be on a trunk route cruising at 80Kph, so those loads will either be delivered outside peak times or dispersed or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consolidated at locations outside the city on to smaller vehicles , including cycles wher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e appropriate in places like Cambridge and York.  With 30% of retail deliveries sufficiently small to be delivered by cargo cycles and small electric vehicles, and 90% of the courier delivered packages weighing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 30Kg (a size &amp; weight easily delivered </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by bike). I can debate the detail of Cycle Logistics separately. Suffice to say that basic economics largely regulates the use of larger vehicles not used in the construction industry</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Only construction sites require a near continuous servicing by trucks d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elivering and removing materials, as machinery cannot stand idle at great cost, and there is no space to stockpile, with an added potential cost of double handling, although there may be ways to investigate that could reduce that cost and manage the lack o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f space for stockpiling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The lack of a Strategic Plan to move large quantities is a key issue preventing the removal of a huge ton-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">milage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of material haulage to &amp; from construction sites, and I fear it is not being effectively addressed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">horizon the demolition of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Heygate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Estate, at Elephant &amp; Castle, with the potential to put at least 200 truck trips per day on to some of the deadliest roads for cycling in London, and this is a likely to add to truck movements linked to London Bridge S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Past examples include the intensive movement of concrete to pour the foundations of The Shard.  30 trucks each with 3 drivers, running 3 shifts round the clock for a ’long’ weekend. Greatly increasing the levels of risk from the hazard of trucks m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oving around the narrow streets of Bermondsey to get to the site.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another example being the Francis Crick site excavation – moving around 3000Tons per day for over 3 months, and, due to the delays of traffic congestion through the city requiring up to 50 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trucks running 150, 63-mile round trips  Had a facility to load on to the railway siding or the canal – both within 1 Km of the site, a faction of the number of trucks would have been required and the footprint of road damage, noise and emissions pollution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, plus the vastly increased risk of crashes through greater exposure on the much longer route. Safety might even have been enhanced by having a short dedicated route a “Lorry Lane” where trucks would run at monitored speeds, probably 20mph or less, and kee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p a steady flow from the site to a barge or train. That site would have converted to 2-3 trains per day, or 38 barges on the Regents Canal      </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Putting these tonnages on the river could really cut down on the mileage being driven (and heightened risk of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crashes) Barges and barge strings of up to 2000T can get up river as far as Battersea – typically ONE tug brings through1500T at a time. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Howver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there is just</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> ONE WHARF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in Central London, with container loading capacity for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 500T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> barges and it can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> ONLY</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> HIGH TIDE.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are also a number of locations where rail sidings or track-beds could be used for loading bulk materials, but the absence of a strategic plan for freight which underwrites the retention </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of  such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> facilities makes the default to truck</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s an inevitable result, if bulk materials need to be moved.  To retain a facility costs a few thousand pounds per year, to keep it “warm” but to reinstate or rebuild something racks the cost into £millions, and a delay of 2-3 years to get it ready – hardly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> synchronised with the sporadic demand from construction projects, to fund themselves.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of course if buildings were repurposed rather than demolished and rebuilt a lot less movement of material would take place, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">teh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> issues around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> need to be examin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed as a holistic approach to reducing truck use.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Fourth Issue – Delivery of impartial investigations which are published</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The committee will be aware of the Rail, Air and Marine Accident Investigation Branches. My own experience in reading the impartia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l reports produced by RAIB lead me to believe a pilot scheme to deliver road crash investigation with the same impartial review of facts and non judgemental analysis of causal factors, which provides a set of recommendations and guidance to prevent the sam</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e incident recurring.  For road crashes at present we have the Police Investigations, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">theses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are not formally published, and they often focus on the delivery of evidence for the prosecution of an offence.  As an interim measure the Police reports could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be redacted if necessary and published but this would fail to deliver changes that are required in the inherent design flaws, in our roads system.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have appended more detail but here are a couple of analyses of fatal crashes in the following notes.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Bow Roundabout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where the decision to send CS2 around the roundabout (where at least 80% of the East-West motor traffic joins the A12 (was A102)) and not over the flyover where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TfL’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> own study recorded 60% of cycle traffic going over the top, and personal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">checking (from Three Mills Cafe – having breakfast and observing cycle traffic) suggests that the figure should be nearer 70%.  Riding over the flyover the potential for a vehicle driving across your path as a cyclist is practically 0% of the minimal motor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> traffic movement (picture in appendix). Whilst using CS2 you have 100% of the motor traffic (excluding some buses) actually driving through the blue strip of paint that 100% of the cycle traffic uses, and the only way the risk of a collision is managed is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by the presumption that cyclists and drivers obey the traffic signals and signage exactly as the designers hope they will. The second attempt is in my view even more deadly that the first, as clearly seen in the video clip used by The Guardian from “SW19”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  We have to ask who or what caused </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ignore the proposals to take cyclists over the flyover</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Papplewick</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A recent coroner’s report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">beggars</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> belief in the conclusions drawn not least the Coroner’s opinion that nothing could be done to curb drivers speed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">filure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to have the point at which the footway traffic – informally this being largely cyclists – crossing the carriageway outside the 30mph limit, and at a point potentially having poor sightlines due to bushes at the roadside, and no detail to h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ighlight the hazard of pedestrian and cycle traffic crossing the carriageway, are all significant factors, which had they been address might have saved a young man’s life.  An RAIB-style report would I believe also have identified the use of the 1 metre wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">de footway as a highly unsafe 2-way cycle route for less confident cyclists travelling outside the village. It might have identified widening and formal adoption</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Fifth Issue – Excise the dangerous drivers before they kill. Using existing legislation</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cotland the Traffic Commissioner – charged with regulating the use of LGV and PCV to ’prevent harm’ has agreed a Memorandum of Understanding with Police Scotland through which she will receive notification of all traffic offences for which a vocational lic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ence holder is stopped and fined.  Currently there is no formal arrangement for the Traffic Commissioners to receive and process every traffic offence that a vocational driver commits, and so we have seen the appalling situation where Denis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Putz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a driver </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with 20 driving bans, and at least 6 significant convictions for Road Traffic Offences, still held a licence to drive the truck he killed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Catriona</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Patel with.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Legislation to deliver this takes time, but the Scots pragmatic approach has the potential to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">liver, a working solution with less delay. I would suggest that a more effective action by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Sir Bernard Hogan-Howe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with the resources of his force might be to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> agree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a similar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Memorandum of Understanding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Nick Denton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Traffic Commissioner Metropolitan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Southeastern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> so that he can call in a driver for formal interview, if that driver’s standard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of driving suggests that they are not a fit person to hold a vocational licence.  From information and intelligence delivered to the Traffic Commissioner, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ey have existing powers to revoke both driving and operating licences where the drivers and operators fail to demonstrate good repute</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What is required is the backing of the Courts and legislators to ensure the Traffic Commissioners can take robust action </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and not be usurped by a cleverly fought appeal, especially when the driver or operator can continue to operate such dangerous vehicles whilst the appeal is heard.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to the interview process there may also be options for the Commissioners to deli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ver short sharp shock penalties of short suspensions of a vocational licence for offences without the formal interview, and also consider the process often used for drivers and pilots after a serious incident when they are in control, and automatically sus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pend the vocational licence of any driver involved in a fatal crash until that driver is formally interviewed by the Commissioner. After all their remit is to regulate and protect the public from harm caused by the activities they regulate.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Design for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">purpose and efficiency</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The operating characteristics of both the individual vehicles and the combined flow characteristics can determine whether measures such as exclusive rights of way (segregation) or a controlled mix (20-25mph* on a carriageway 10-15mp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h* on a combined carriageway &amp; footway)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">*The figures may need to be refined by research and experience, BUT evolution has delivered a healthy human with a maximum unaided/unprotected operating speed of the running man – around 20mph (1 mile in  3 minutes)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – a speed at which falling over, running into things and above which the full width visual observation begins to diminish.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On rail systems, when a particular traffic becomes dominant the railway provides a goods, fast, or slow line, and can often look to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> grade separation to keep flows running smoothly and safely where routes intersect.  The may be some benefits to be gained from getting cycle routes up in the sky, and moving to taking over road-space big time where flows are reaching the level where the p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">articular operating parameters of cycles (and other traffic, on foot, motorised etc) will work to best effect   I’ve put some ideas in the appendix  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>